To all the moms…

You are seen, you are noticed and appreciated. I was talking to a mama the other day and she asked me, “How do you do it with 5?! I only have one!” 

I told her whether you have 1 or 5, being a mom is hard. You often feel overwhelmed, stretched to the max. You constantly ask yourself, am I doing enough? 

In this crazy busy season, we are pulled in a million directions. Going to all the things. 

Our days are filled with the mundane tasks. Drop off and pick up lines. The grocery store for the 62652 time this week. Packing lunches every single day. Endless loads of laundry and dishes. Sweeping the floor again, even though you just did it. 

I’m trying to remind myself that those tasks that feel so monotonous and repetitive, are what my family needs. The every day to-do lists help everything else fall into place and run smoothly. 

Trying to appreciate the little things and be thankful for them, so when the big moments come, we are extra thankful. Celebrating the little moments with my kids. My son who was the high scorer in his basketball game. A dance party with my girls because we all needed it. My son who got dressed up for me and waited for me to get home because he wanted to dance with me to our song, all the goodbye kisses when you drop off another at practice. 

Each of those moments matter. Those little things that you feel are small, are what your kids will remember. 

Mamas, you are seen, loved, and appreciated.

As I reflect on this year, my family and I went through a lot of firsts. 

Our kids went to school full time for the first time. I hung up my homeschooling hat and handed my kids over to a new school. We prayed about this new transition for a long time and trusted the Lord. This new season wasn’t always easy but we have peace knowing it was the right thing for our family. That was a first. 

We became parents of a first time driver, for the first time. Seeing my son drive away for the first time, on his own, without me, was heart wrenching. Did I prepare him enough? Did I teach him enough? Will he be safe? I once again had to lean on the Lord and trust that He will be with my son every time he sits behind the wheel. That was a first. 

My husband stepped into a new role at our church. Learning how to be a shepherd’s wife was super intimidating. I felt so ill equipped most of the time. But watching him lead has been so inspiring. That was a first. 

I stepped into a couple new roles for the first time. I got hired as a head coach for our school’s middle school volleyball team. Stepping into one of my passions as a head coach was exciting yet terrifying. Will I be good enough to coach them? Will they respect and like me as a coach? The season was tough, but I learned so much. Our team went through a lot together. Grieving the loss of a school mate, a hard season, a new coach, getting to know each other. But at the end of the season they all asked me if I was coming back next season and many expressed what an amazing impact I had on them. Little did they know, they had a major impact me. They helped me grow, taught me so much, and I’m honored to say, I’ll be their head coach again next season. That was a first. 

I stepped into a role I never thought I’d undertake. Saying yes to a new venture that I swore I’d never do. Teaming up with incredible women who challenged me, helped me see potential in myself that I didn’t know was there or even believed. Becoming “that girl” was intimidating and so scary but so glad I said yes and dove head first. That was a first. 

While this year threw a lot of firsts for me, it has prepared me for what’s to come! Bring it on 2023!

This is 38!

Today is my birthday, and each year as I get older, I enjoy it more and more, and look forward to another year. I like getting older. 

This year felt different. A few weeks ago, I had a turning point, eye opening moment. I had hit a wall. I wasn’t myself, physically, mentally, and spiritually. I’ve been gaining weight even though I work out. I was tuned out and just going through the motions of life. I was sad. I disliked how I looked and felt. I finally admitted to my husband and to myself, (not sure which one was harder), that I’m struggling and I need help. 

The next morning I was doing some research and then scrolling social media. The first post I see was our former nanny. She has become a certified nutritionist, who dives deep into women’s health. I knew her post was what I was suppose to see that morning. I instantly knew what I needed to do. 

I realized my entire body is out of whack, therefore throwing all of my hormones off and affecting my emotional and physical health. Her and I are working together to figure it all out. She has created a health roadmap for me to get me where I want to be and achieve goals I’ve set for myself. 

The past few weeks have been really hard. I’ve had really hard conversations. Hard realizations. 

But….I have a plan. 

I know the process will be hard but worth it. I’m working on myself for my husband. For my kids. For myself. I’m holding myself accountable. I want to be able to look back on all this and realize how far I’ve come. See the growth. See the change. Welcome to my journey!

This is 38!

It hit my hubby and I hard this morning that he won’t be here everyday to be a big brother to his little bro and they can go throw the lax ball until dark together. He won’t be here everyday to be his sissy’s best friend. He won’t be here everyday to have a comedy session with his bug. He won’t be here everyday to take care of his Claire bear. But I know this kid is going to succeed and change the world. I am honored to be his mama and he changed my world the moment he came into it!
